5–1388","1368–1388":"1368–1388","1376–1408":"1376–1408","1320–1375":"1320–1375","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1368":"1368","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1355":"1355","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","about 1376":"about 1376","about 1355":"about 1355","1408":"1408","after 1388":"after 1388","Norries, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","North Huish, Devonshire, England":"North Huish, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bray, Maidenhead, Berkshire, England":"Bray, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Norreys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Norris  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Norris","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Middle English <i>norreis</i>, <i>noreis</i>, <i>norais</i> ‘northerner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>noreis</i>), used both of Norwegians and of inhabitants of northern England and Scotland.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Norreis</i>, derived from <i>norreis</i> ‘northerner’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Norreys was born about 1355, in North Huish, Devon, England, United Kingdom,